reviews.review_text: vintage underground radio Here's a real cool slice of  the very early days of San Francisco FM freeform radio with the maestro, Tom Donahue.Tom would take the KMPX staff over to KSAN a year later after a bitter strike with station owners. Jerry and Phil come across as real intelligent guys here and the music they select for Tom to play is very good.

Time Slice This is a little gem to add to anyone's collection. In those early, early days it's a treat to now see and hear how involved they were in the whole tapistry of American music, including the Charles Ives Syymphony #4. There is a difference between being musicians and being taken seriously as artists I think, and this view of Jerry's (and the bands') 'holistic' repertoire is very reflective of their desire to become unique and at the same time represent their musical influences. These artists, as represented here with the selections on the radio show, offer a broad spectrum of a constantly changing and endowed musical heritage.
   Thanks for making this available.

Jerry and Phil's favorites! What a treat to hear what Jerry and Phil were listening to in '67!  A true insight into what influenced the Grateful.  Interesting how much respect they have for the Beatles, and to a lesser extent Motown (they took Dancin' as their own).  I've been listening to The Boys for many a moon, and it's great to hear this bit of musical history.  

Download and enjoy!
Great I thought this was a great collection builder.  Would like to hear more of this

Cool Daddy-O Aside from the novelty of these odd ducks talking music, the tunes are, for the most part, outstanding. On the strength of these samples, I just added the Junior Wells and the Charles Lloyd albums to my collection. Excellent stuff. This goes to show you what's missing in radio. Once upon a time, we could benefit from a knowledgable DJ lighting the way. Now we're all forced to blaze our own trails, and missing plenty along the way, no doubt. How do you rate something like this? I certainly got 5 stars of enjoyment out of it, and a little education too. For those too young to remember, it may sound pretty corny, but I love this.

history lesson this is a great piece of americana.  i'm currently studying to be a radio dj, and i must say, this is all i ever need to study.  not only is this a necessity for gd fans, but like mentioned above, this is a necessity for any fan of american music from blues to the dead.  the quality of the download is worth the listen alone!
swan silvertones A bit of the first record can be heard at www.jive95.com in the "roots of ksan" section.
its grateful its cool to listen to the sound is so listen to. Its a crazy thing to listen to the 60s dead then listen to the other years there sound progressed so much along the years

Great set list and interview This is an eclectic set of good music, from soul, jazz, folk, blues, rock, and avante garde classical (Charles Ives, early 20th century). (Interesting how there is nothing from the SF scene of the time -- no Airplane, etc.) A good set to listen to on it's own, with interviews of Jerry and Phil talking about jazz, the Beatles, and various other things musical.

They also talk about the first Dead album which had just come out a few weeks previously. It was the number 1 album in San Francisco at the time, but they're pretty down on it. Phil calls it "a turd."
Fantastic Interview Material !!! So early! Jerry says' bobby used to sing "She Belongs To Me"? Where's that tape?
A classic moment in history This is radio history.

WoW This is truly a treasure, while there are ton of incredible Dead shows to listen to this one is truly unique.  The banter between Jerry and Phil along with them picking out who to listen to is AWSOME.  We all have numerous musical influences but to hear those that touched these guys at such a pivitol time period is one of the truly golden moments that only the archive can provide.  Thanx to all you wonderful Deadheads out there, and enjoy this recording.

"DJs" Phil and Jerry I'm surprised nobody has ever commented on this. Basically it's Phil and Jerry commenting on a bunch of songs they like. You get their take on Otis Redding vs. James Brown and other curiosities. Not really a "must listen" but worth checking out.
- Very interesting, great and eclectic mixture of music.

This is Golden Radio...Unlimited Devotion A surprising play list put together by Jerry & Phil.  Very soulful and introspective.  Awesome and fun to listen to, especially the radio ads and the banter.  Thanks for making this available.

Essential GD Jerry & Phil bringing in their favorite tunes 
and discussing the same with a noted local DJ. 
and the year is 1967. *****
(just after the 1st LP was released.)
Golden Road 
BIODTL
Rain And Snow 
Sittin' On Top Of The World 
Cream Puff War -Jerry (only original on the LP)
Morning Dew 
New, New Minglewood Blues 
Viola Lee Blues 

Not sure you can get a more candid insight
into the future leanings of the band.

They left Weir at home
but he does contribute
a Maggie's Farm by Dylan
to the playlist.

It always interests me to see what creative people
have in their music and book collections

To the DJ's credit 
he mainly let's Phil & Jerry
carry the evening

As far as the music
Charles Lloyd -has Dark Star jam written all over it

Jerry gives a nice tribute to seeing Otis live
and then play Otis covering 'Daytripper'

This is pretty.. Awesome..

In fact, it's absolutely priceless..
Gotta Love Tom's Radio cadence and professionalism, he is the king of Camelot..
San Francisco 1967 FM, nuff 'caid..
(google his image, big boy, amazing)

Jerry is engaged, Phillip seems slurred,
but the music selection is Grade 'A'.

Thanks for yet another Beautron..Where else could anyone find this? Ever?

Dank  Listening to this in July 2020, how cool, what a find! So fun to hear all these great selections, some completely new to me, others I knew the name of the artist but not not much else... really dug Charles Mingus... others well known but have not finished it yet. Fun to hear the chatter about the "new" dead LP... glad that the ensemble of the Bulgarian republic was short, interested but not an LP I will be seeking out, and neither will you! hahahaha ( I dont want to seem presumptuous) but it sounds like Yoko, not good Yoko but screaming Yoko...did not finish listening to all of this yet

Taking Mr Back About this time our French teacher told us about KMPX & I learned you could built a wire clothes-hanger antenna cut to the exact length to pick up the station,  which was 50 mi. north from my home in Los Gatos.

I hated Top-40's 2:30-min talk-over-the-intro format.  The first song I dialed into with my new antenna was Bob Dylan's 22-min. 'Sad Eyed Lady of the Lowlands'. Heaven.

Tom Donohue is still the greatest 'underground' DJ ever.
